    <item>
      <title></title>
      <link>https://vardahagh.com/authors/admin/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 05 Feb 2019 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      
      <guid>https://vardahagh.com/authors/admin/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;I am a postdoctoral researcher at the James Franck Institute of the University of Chicago, and a member of the Simons Collaboration on Cracking the Glass Problem. I am mostly fascinated by the ideas of material training and memory formation in disordered materials.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Training in this context refers to starting with a generic material, with ordinary physical properties and function, and evolving its microscopic features such that the system finds a new equilibrium state with novel properties and extraordinary function. For instance, most materials have a positive Poisson’s ratio, but if you put them under compression, you can change their local properties such that the material develops a negative Poisson’s ratio.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;By memory formation, we mean the ability of a physical system to remember a previous mechanical deformation. I am interested in mechanisms that lead to such behavior.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I am also interested in studying mechanical systems that rigidify under tension (and thus are second-order rigid). In particular, designing mechanical metamaterials that change their shape due to changes in local tension is of high interest to me because there is a large space to explore creatively.&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
